{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018Dd3u1oeodkCy7ZYXmwT1z","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Review complete. Here is a summary of what was done:\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/Dockerfile` — Added `ENTRYPOINT [\"codeharness\"]`, `npm cache clean --force`, explicit workspace dir creation with correct ownership\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/.dockerignore` — Expanded from 4 to 18 entries to prevent ~85MB of unnecessary files from entering build context\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/7-3-create-dockerfile.md` — Status set to `verifying`, review notes appended, File List and Change Log updated\n\n**Verification results:**\n- All 6 Dockerfile validator rules pass\n- 2930 unit tests pass, 0 regressions\n- Coverage: 97.02% overall, all 123 files above the 80% per-file floor (exceeds the 90% overall target)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and their severity:**\n- **HIGH** — `.dockerignore` only excluded `.env`, `.git`, `node_modules`. The docker build context included ~85MB of unnecessary files (ralph 74MB, src 4.7MB, _bmad 1.8MB, _bmad-output 3.3MB, coverage, test, etc.). Fixed.\n- **HIGH** — No `ENTRYPOINT` instruction. Container required explicitly passing `codeharness` as an argument to `docker run`. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM** — No `npm cache clean --force` after `npm install -g`, leaving npm cache in the image layer. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM** — `WORKDIR /workspace` created after `USER node` without explicit ownership setup. Fixed with `mkdir -p && chown`.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt):**\n- **LOW** — No `HEALTHCHECK` instruction. Acceptable for a CLI tool container, but if this Dockerfile is meant to be the \"exemplar\" that passes codeharness's own audit, a HEALTHCHECK would be best practice for service-oriented containers. Not required by the validator's 6 rules.\n- **LOW** — COPY tarball in a separate layer from the RUN that deletes it. The tarball persists in the intermediate COPY layer even though it's deleted in the next RUN layer. Fixing this properly requires BuildKit `--mount=type=bind` which changes the build command UX. Tech debt.\n- **LOW** — `templates/Dockerfile.verify` also lacks `USER node` (runs as root). The story correctly notes this is by design for verification environments, but it's worth flagging as a hardening opportunity.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- None. No new TypeScript code was added. Existing `dockerfile-validator.test.ts` has comprehensive coverage of all 6 rules. Overall coverage is 97.02%.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- The `checkVerificationTools` function in `dockerfile-validator.ts` checks tools line-by-line. If a Dockerfile uses multiline `apt-get install` with backslash continuation where a tool name appears on a continuation line (not the same line as `apt-get install`), it would falsely report the tool as missing. The dev agent already discovered and documented this. It's a validator limitation, not a Dockerfile issue, but it constrains how Dockerfiles can be formatted.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues were fixed in this review session."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a72395e913af6e5db (use SendMessage with to: 'a72395e913af6e5db' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 49762\ntool_uses: 37\nduration_ms: 217434</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d92c7bcb-37ff-4aa2-841f-ece7fabef071","uuid":"dea49170-761c-4540-959f-7ef243cd37d4","timestamp":"2026-03-21T12:36:37.864Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/7-3-create-dockerfile.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a72395e913af6e5db","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Review complete. Here is a summary of what was done:\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/Dockerfile` — Added `ENTRYPOINT [\"codeharness\"]`, `npm cache clean --force`, explicit workspace dir creation with correct ownership\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/.dockerignore` — Expanded from 4 to 18 entries to prevent ~85MB of unnecessary files from entering build context\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/7-3-create-dockerfile.md` — Status set to `verifying`, review notes appended, File List and Change Log updated\n\n**Verification results:**\n- All 6 Dockerfile validator rules pass\n- 2930 unit tests pass, 0 regressions\n- Coverage: 97.02% overall, all 123 files above the 80% per-file floor (exceeds the 90% overall target)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and their severity:**\n- **HIGH** — `.dockerignore` only excluded `.env`, `.git`, `node_modules`. The docker build context included ~85MB of unnecessary files (ralph 74MB, src 4.7MB, _bmad 1.8MB, _bmad-output 3.3MB, coverage, test, etc.). Fixed.\n- **HIGH** — No `ENTRYPOINT` instruction. Container required explicitly passing `codeharness` as an argument to `docker run`. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM** — No `npm cache clean --force` after `npm install -g`, leaving npm cache in the image layer. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM** — `WORKDIR /workspace` created after `USER node` without explicit ownership setup. Fixed with `mkdir -p && chown`.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt):**\n- **LOW** — No `HEALTHCHECK` instruction. Acceptable for a CLI tool container, but if this Dockerfile is meant to be the \"exemplar\" that passes codeharness's own audit, a HEALTHCHECK would be best practice for service-oriented containers. Not required by the validator's 6 rules.\n- **LOW** — COPY tarball in a separate layer from the RUN that deletes it. The tarball persists in the intermediate COPY layer even though it's deleted in the next RUN layer. Fixing this properly requires BuildKit `--mount=type=bind` which changes the build command UX. Tech debt.\n- **LOW** — `templates/Dockerfile.verify` also lacks `USER node` (runs as root). The story correctly notes this is by design for verification environments, but it's worth flagging as a hardening opportunity.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- None. No new TypeScript code was added. Existing `dockerfile-validator.test.ts` has comprehensive coverage of all 6 rules. Overall coverage is 97.02%.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- The `checkVerificationTools` function in `dockerfile-validator.ts` checks tools line-by-line. If a Dockerfile uses multiline `apt-get install` with backslash continuation where a tool name appears on a continuation line (not the same line as `apt-get install`), it would falsely report the tool as missing. The dev agent already discovered and documented this. It's a validator limitation, not a Dockerfile issue, but it constrains how Dockerfiles can be formatted.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues were fixed in this review session."}],"totalDurationMs":217434,"totalTokens":49762,"totalToolUseCount":37,"usage":{