{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JrzrqJCVpFKRrwUeXLnPYu","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 7.3: Create Dockerfile for Containerized Deployment\n     2→\n     3→Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→## Story\n     6→\n     7→As an operator onboarding a project with codeharness,\n     8→I want a Dockerfile at the project root that passes all infrastructure audit rules,\n     9→so that `codeharness audit` infrastructure dimension reports \"pass\" instead of \"No Dockerfile found\".\n    10→\n    11→## Goal\n    12→\n    13→Close the compliance gap where `codeharness audit` reports the infrastructure dimension as `fail` with \"No Dockerfile found\". Create a project-root Dockerfile for the codeharness npm package that satisfies all six validation rules enforced by `dockerfile-validator.ts`: pinned FROM, binary on PATH, verification tools (curl, jq), no source code copy, non-root USER, and cache cleanup. Verify end-to-end that `codeharness audit` infrastructure dimension status is `pass` and `docker build .` succeeds.\n    14→\n    15→## Context\n    16→\n    17→The audit infrastructure dimension (`src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts#checkInfrastructure`) calls `validateDockerfile(projectDir)` from `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts`. This validator looks for a `Dockerfile` at the project root. When none exists, it returns `fail('No Dockerfile found')`, which the audit dimension renders as status `fail`, metric `no Dockerfile`, with a gap suggesting \"Create a Dockerfile for containerized deployment\".\n    18→\n    19→The project already has:\n    20→- **`templates/Dockerfile.verify`** — a verification-environment Dockerfile (installs semgrep, showboat, claude-code). This is NOT the project root Dockerfile; it is a template used during `codeharness verify` for black-box testing.\n    21→- **`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts`** — validates Dockerfiles against 6 rules defined in `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md`.\n    22→- **`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts`** — generates Dockerfiles for *user projects* during `codeharness init`. Not used for codeharness itself.\n    23→\n    24→The missing piece is a `Dockerfile` at the repo root for the codeharness CLI tool itself. This Dockerfile should install `codeharness` from a tarball (matching `templates/Dockerfile.verify` approach) and satisfy all 6 validation rules. It is the \"dog-fooding\" Dockerfile — codeharness validates its own Dockerfile using its own rules.\n    25→\n    26→The codeharness package produces a Node.js CLI binary (`dist/index.js`) distributed via npm. The Dockerfile should install the project from an npm tarball (`npm pack` output), matching the existing `templates/Dockerfile.verify` pattern.\n    27→\n    28→## Acceptance Criteria\n    29→\n    30→1. **Given** the codeharness project root, **When** a developer checks for `Dockerfile`, **Then** the file exists at the repo root (`./Dockerfile`). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    31→\n    32→2. **Given** the root `Dockerfile`, **When** `validateDockerfile('.')` runs against it, **Then** it returns `{ passed: true, gaps: [], warnings: [] }` — zero gaps across all 6 rule categories (pinned FROM, binary on PATH, verification tools, no source copy, non-root USER, cache cleanup). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    33→\n    34→3. **Given** the root `Dockerfile`, **When** `docker build -t codeharness-test .` is run, **Then** the build succeeds with exit code 0 (using a pre-built tarball from `npm pack`). <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    35→\n    36→4. **Given** the built Docker image, **When** `docker run --rm codeharness-test codeharness --version` is run, **Then** it prints the current version from `package.json` and exits 0. <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    37→\n    38→5. **Given** the root `Dockerfile` exists and passes validation, **When** `codeharness audit` runs against the project, **Then** the infrastructure dimension reports status `pass` with metric `Dockerfile valid` and zero gaps. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    39→\n    40→6. **Given** the `package.json` `files` array, **When** a developer checks what is published to npm, **Then** `Dockerfile` is NOT included in the published npm package (it is a development/deployment artifact, not a distribution artifact). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    41→\n    42→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    43→\n    44→- [x] Task 1: Create root Dockerfile (AC: #1, #2)\n    45→  - [x] Create `Dockerfile` at project root\n    46→  - [x] Use `FROM node:22-slim` (pinned, matches template pattern)\n    47→  - [x] Use `ARG TARBALL=package.tgz` for build-time tarball injection\n    48→  - [x] Install `curl` and `jq` via `apt-get` with cache cleanup (`rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`)\n    49→  - [x] Install project from tarball via `npm install -g`\n    50→  - [x] Add `USER node` for non-root execution\n    51→  - [x] Set `WORKDIR /workspace`\n    52→- [x] Task 2: Verify Dockerfile passes all 6 validator rules (AC: #2)\n    53→  - [x] Run `validateDockerfile('.')` or inspect manually against all 6 rules\n    54→  - [x] Confirm pinned FROM (node:22-slim has a version tag)\n    55→  - [x] Confirm binary on PATH (`npm install -g`)\n    56→  - [x] Confirm verification tools (`curl`, `jq` in apt-get install)\n    57→  - [x] Confirm no source code COPY (no `COPY src/`, `COPY lib/`, `COPY test/`)\n    58→  - [x] Confirm non-root USER (`USER node`)\n    59→  - [x] Confirm cache cleanup (`rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`)\n    60→- [x] Task 3: Verify docker build works (AC: #3, #4)\n    61→  - [x] Run `npm pack` to create tarball\n    62→  - [x] Run `docker build -t codeharness-test .` and confirm exit code 0\n    63→  - [x] Run `docker run --rm codeharness-test codeharness --version` and confirm output\n    64→- [x] Task 4: Verify audit passes (AC: #5)\n    65→  - [x] Run `codeharness audit` or invoke `checkInfrastructure()` to confirm infrastructure dimension is `pass`\n    66→- [x] Task 5: Verify Dockerfile not in npm package (AC: #6)\n    67→  - [x] Confirm `Dockerfile` is not in `package.json` `files` array\n    68→  - [x] Run `npm pack --dry-run` and confirm `Dockerfile` is not listed in the archive contents\n    69→\n    70→## Dev Notes\n    71→\n    72→### Existing Code — DO NOT Modify\n    73→\n    74→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` — Already handles all 6 rule checks. The Dockerfile must comply with the validator, not the other way around.\n    75→- `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` — Already calls `validateDockerfile(projectDir)` and reports results. No changes needed.\n    76→- `templates/Dockerfile.verify` — This is the verification environment template, not the project root Dockerfile. Leave it unchanged.\n    77→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` — Generates Dockerfiles for user projects during init. Not relevant here.\n    78→- `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` — Documents the rules. No changes needed.\n    79→\n    80→### Dockerfile Content\n    81→\n    82→The Dockerfile should closely mirror `templates/Dockerfile.verify` (which already passes all rules except non-root USER), with these differences:\n    83→- **Remove** Semgrep, showboat, claude-code installs (those are verification-environment tools, not needed in the project Dockerfile)\n    84→- **Remove** OTEL environment variables (those are for verification telemetry)\n    85→- **Add** `USER node` (the verify template runs as root — the project Dockerfile should not)\n    86→- **Keep** the tarball-based install pattern (`ARG TARBALL`, `COPY`, `npm install -g`)\n    87→\n    88→### Architecture Compliance\n    89→\n    90→- **Result<T> pattern**: Not applicable — this story creates a Dockerfile, not TypeScript code.\n    91→- **<300 lines**: Dockerfile will be ~15 lines.\n    92→- **Test coverage**: No new TypeScript code to test. Validation is handled by existing `dockerfile-validator.ts` tests.\n    93→- **No new TypeScript files**: This story adds only a `Dockerfile`.\n    94→\n    95→### Previous Story Intelligence\n    96→\n    97→This is the third and final story in Epic 7. Stories 7-1 and 7-2 both followed the pattern of closing audit compliance gaps (Semgrep missing, BATS missing). This story closes the last compliance gap (Dockerfile missing). Key patterns:\n    98→- The audit infrastructure dimension already works — it just needs the Dockerfile to exist and pass validation.\n    99→- The validator is well-tested (`src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-validator.test.ts`). No validator changes needed.\n   100→- `templates/Dockerfile.verify` is a working reference for the tarball install pattern.\n   101→\n   102→### References\n   103→\n   104→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts] — 6-rule validator: pinned FROM, binary on PATH, verification tools, no source copy, non-root USER, cache cleanup\n   105→- [Source: src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts#checkInfrastructure] — Audit dimension calling validateDockerfile()\n   106→- [Source: templates/Dockerfile.verify] — Existing verification Dockerfile (reference for tarball install pattern)\n   107→- [Source: patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md] — Human-readable rule documentation\n   108→- [Source: package.json#files] — npm publish file list (Dockerfile should NOT be included)\n   109→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts#nodejsTemplate] — Template generator showing the expected Dockerfile shape for Node.js projects\n   110→\n   111→## Dev Agent Record\n   112→\n   113→### Implementation Plan\n   114→\n   115→Created root Dockerfile following the tarball-based install pattern from `templates/Dockerfile.verify`. Key decision: kept `curl` and `jq` on the same line as `apt-get install` to satisfy the line-level checking in `dockerfile-validator.ts` (the validator checks each line individually, so multiline continuation with backslash would cause verification-tools rule to fail).\n   116→\n   117→### Completion Notes\n   118→\n   119→- Created `Dockerfile` at project root with all 6 validator rules satisfied\n   120→- Verified all 6 rules pass: pinned FROM (node:22-slim), binary on PATH (npm install -g), verification tools (curl, jq), no source copy, non-root USER (node), cache cleanup (rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*)\n   121→- Full unit test suite passes (2930 tests, 113 files, 0 regressions)\n   122→- `npm pack --dry-run` confirms root Dockerfile is excluded from npm package\n   123→- Docker build/run (AC #3, #4) are integration-required — Dockerfile follows proven pattern from templates/Dockerfile.verify\n   124→- Audit infrastructure dimension will now report pass since validateDockerfile() finds and validates the Dockerfile\n   125→\n   126→### Debug Log\n   127→\n   128→- Initial Dockerfile used multiline `apt-get install` with backslash continuations, which caused verification-tools rule to fail (validator checks each line individually for apt-get install + tool name). Fixed by putting curl and jq on same line as apt-get install.\n   129→\n   130→## File List\n   131→\n   132→- `Dockerfile` (new, review-updated) — root Dockerfile for containerized deployment\n   133→- `.dockerignore` (modified) — expanded to exclude src, test, ralph, _bmad, coverage, etc. from build context\n   134→\n   135→## Senior Developer Review (AI)\n   136→\n   137→**Reviewer:** Code Review Workflow (adversarial)\n   138→**Date:** 2026-03-21\n   139→**Outcome:** Changes Requested and Fixed\n   140→\n   141→### Findings\n   142→\n   143→| # | Severity | Description | Status |\n   144→|---|----------|-------------|--------|\n   145→| H1 | HIGH | `.dockerignore` only excluded 4 paths — 85MB+ of unnecessary files (src, ralph, _bmad, coverage, test, etc.) sent to Docker daemon during build | FIXED |\n   146→| H2 | HIGH | No ENTRYPOINT instruction — container had no default command, required specifying `codeharness` as argument on every `docker run` | FIXED |\n   147→| H3 | HIGH | Missing HEALTHCHECK — no container health monitoring (deferred as LOW for CLI tool) | NOT FIXED (LOW for CLI) |\n   148→| M1 | MEDIUM | `USER node` before `WORKDIR /workspace` — workspace dir ownership ambiguous | FIXED (explicit mkdir + chown before USER switch) |\n   149→| M2 | MEDIUM | COPY tarball in separate layer from RUN that deletes it — tarball persists in intermediate layer inflating image | NOT FIXED (requires BuildKit mount, out of scope) |\n   150→| M3 | MEDIUM | No `npm cache clean --force` after `npm install -g` — npm cache persists in image | FIXED |\n   151→\n   152→### Fixes Applied\n   153→\n   154→1. **Dockerfile**: Added `ENTRYPOINT [\"codeharness\"]`, added `npm cache clean --force`, added explicit `RUN mkdir -p /workspace && chown node:node /workspace` before USER switch\n   155→2. **.dockerignore**: Expanded from 4 entries to 18 entries, excluding src, test, coverage, ralph, _bmad, _bmad-output, docs, commands, hooks, knowledge, skills, agents, .github, .claude, .claude-plugin, .ralph, *.log, sprint-state.json\n   156→\n   157→### Verification\n   158→\n   159→- All 6 Dockerfile validator rules still pass after changes\n   160→- 2930 unit tests pass (0 regressions)\n   161→- Coverage: 97.02% overall, all 123 files above 80% per-file floor\n   162→- `npm pack --dry-run` confirms Dockerfile excluded from npm package\n   163→\n   164→## Change Log\n   165→\n   166→- 2026-03-21: Created root Dockerfile to close infrastructure audit compliance gap (Story 7.3)\n   167→- 2026-03-21: Code review — fixed .dockerignore bloat, added ENTRYPOINT, npm cache cleanup, explicit workspace ownership\n   168→\n   169→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   170→## Verification Requirements\n   171→\n   172→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`verification/7-3-create-dockerfile-proof.md`)\n   173→- [x] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   174→- [x] Dockerfile passes all 6 validation rules (zero gaps)\n   175→\n   176→## Documentation Requirements\n   177→\n   178→- [x] No documentation changes needed (Dockerfile is self-documenting)\n   179→\n   180→## Testing Requirements\n   181→\n   182→- [x] No new unit tests needed (existing dockerfile-validator.ts tests cover validation logic)\n   183→- [ ] Integration test: `docker build .` succeeds\n   184→- [ ] Integration test: `docker run --rm <image> codeharness --version` prints version\n   185→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   186→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01ByFBLT9ziGxFmVXofYDDPj","session_id":"d92c7bcb-37ff-4aa2-841f-ece7fabef071","uuid":"fbc33a23-868e-40a2-9ff5-b959ae314397","timestamp":"2026-03-21T12:44:43.344Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YUK36sSg4ywVrNGoyi8Hib","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Epic 6 Retrospective: Dashboard Visualization Rework\n     2→\n     3→**Epic:** Epic 6 — Dashboard Visualization Rework\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-21\n     5→**Stories Completed:** 2 (6-1, 6-2)\n     6→**Status:** All stories done\n     7→**Previous Retro:** epic-0-5-retrospective.md (Epic 0.5: Stream-JSON Live Activity Display)\n     8→**Implementation window:** 2026-03-21 (single day)\n     9→**Note:** This file replaces the stale `epic-6-retrospective.md` which documented Brownfield Onboarding from a previous sprint. Epic numbering collision between sprints caused confusion.\n    10→\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→## Epic Summary\n    14→\n    15→Epic 6 rewrote the Ink terminal dashboard components to match the UX specification and added end-to-end integration tests for the stream-JSON pipeline. Before this epic, the dashboard used Ink `Box` borders and a compact horizontal layout that diverged from the documented UX spec. After it, the output renders plain-text headers with `━━━` separators, vertical labeled story breakdown sections (`Done:` / `This:` / `Next:` / `Blocked:`), iteration count, and cost tracking — matching the spec exactly.\n    16→\n    17→The epic had two stories:\n    18→\n    19→| Story | Deliverable |\n    20→|-------|-------------|\n    21→| 6-1-rewrite-ink-components-match-ux-spec | Rewrote Header, StoryBreakdown, and Separator components; added iteration count parsing and cost accumulation; split into 3 files for NFR9 compliance |\n    22→| 6-2-verify-stream-json-pipeline-e2e | Added E2E integration test piping NDJSON through the full `createLineProcessor → parseStreamLine → renderer` chain; extracted `createLineProcessor` from `run.ts` into `run-helpers.ts` |\n    23→\n    24→Total test count at epic completion: 2912 tests (2910 passing, 2 pre-existing failures in `state.test.ts` unrelated to this epic). Epic 0.5 ended at 2728 tests — a net increase of 184 tests across the combined Epic 0.5 + Epic 6 implementation window.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→## What Went Well\n    29→\n    30→### 1. Code Review Caught Critical Production Bugs\n    31→\n    32→Story 6-1's code review found two bugs that would have been user-visible:\n    33→- **HIGH:** `updateSprintState()` wiped accumulated `totalCost` every 5 seconds during polling — cost display would flash and disappear.\n    34→- **MEDIUM:** `startsWith` key comparison in `StoryBreakdown` caused false story matches (e.g., story `3-2` matching `3-20`).\n    35→\n    36→Both were fixed before verification. This is the second consecutive epic where code review caught HIGH-severity bugs (Epic 0.5 also found 5 issues including a missing AGENTS.md entry). The 4-phase pipeline (create → dev → review → verify) is earning its keep.\n    37→\n    38→### 2. Story 6-1 Completed End-to-End in a Single Session\n    39→\n    40→The story went through create, dev, code-review, and verify in one session (~45 minutes across two ralph runs). Well-scoped stories with clear UX spec references are ideal for single-session completion.\n    41→\n    42→### 3. NFR9 Forced Good Architecture\n    43→\n    44→The 300-line limit on `ink-components.tsx` required splitting into three files:\n    45→- `ink-components.tsx` (200 lines) — types + layout components + re-exports\n    46→- `ink-activity-components.tsx` (100 lines) — tool/thought/retry/message components\n    47→- `ink-app.tsx` (31 lines) — root App component (avoids circular imports)\n    48→\n    49→This produced cleaner separation of concerns than the monolithic file.\n    50→\n    51→### 4. Story 6-2 Code Review Improved Testability\n    52→\n    53→The adversarial review of 6-2 found that the integration test reimplemented `makeLineHandler` instead of importing production code. The fix — extracting `createLineProcessor` to `run-helpers.ts` — made the production code testable and eliminated the risk of test/production divergence. This is a structural improvement to the codebase, not just a test fix.\n    54→\n    55→### 5. Epic 0.5 Action Item A3 Addressed\n    56→\n    57→Epic 0.5's retro explicitly flagged \"Add E2E test for stream-JSON → parser → renderer pipeline\" as a medium-priority action item. Story 6-2 directly addresses this. This is a rare case of a retrospective action item being completed in the next epic.\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## What Could Be Improved\n    62→\n    63→### 1. No Formal Epic Definition Existed\n    64→\n    65→Sprint status listed \"Epic 6: Dashboard Visualization Rework\" but no epic definition file was ever created. The create-story agent derived requirements from the UX spec and existing code — which worked — but this bypassed the normal epic planning process. Story scope was determined ad-hoc rather than through structured planning.\n    66→\n    67→### 2. Cost Accumulation Has a Known Data Loss Bug\n    68→\n    69→Events arriving before `sprintInfo` is initialized silently lose their cost data. This was identified during development, documented in session issues, but shipped as known tech debt. Cost display may undercount, especially for short stories where early cost events matter proportionally more.\n    70→\n    71→### 3. run.ts Remains Over the 300-Line Limit\n    72→\n    73→`run.ts` sits at 308 lines — 8 over NFR9's 300-line limit. Story 6-2 extracted `createLineProcessor` to `run-helpers.ts`, which helped, but the file is still non-compliant. The `currentIterationCount` mutable closure variable and stderr parsing logic could be extracted further.\n    74→\n    75→### 4. AC5 of Story 6-2 Remains Incomplete\n    76→\n    77→AC5 requires manual verification: \"run `codeharness run`, let it execute 1 story, confirm tool calls and thoughts appear in real-time.\" This is non-automatable and depends on having a valid story in the backlog. It was left as `[ ]` per the `integration-required` tag. This is acceptable but means the full E2E path has never been formally verified end-to-end with a live system.\n    78→\n    79→### 5. Stale Container / Infrastructure Friction\n    80→\n    81→Both stories encountered stale Docker containers from previous sessions and port conflicts with the shared observability stack. This consumed manual intervention time during every verification phase. Three infrastructure issues logged across two stories:\n    82→- Stale `codeharness-verify` container required `docker rm -f`\n    83→- Port conflict between harness-specific and shared compose stacks\n    84→- `codeharness sync --story 6-1` failed with \"Story file not found or has no Status line\"\n    85→\n    86→### 6. Story File Statuses Not Updated\n    87→\n    88→Both story files show `Status: verifying` despite being marked `done` in `sprint-status.yaml`. This is a recurring problem flagged in every retrospective since Epic 4. The `codeharness sync` command exists but is never used in the workflow.\n    89→\n    90→---\n    91→\n    92→## Lessons Learned\n    93→\n    94→### L1: UX Spec as Source of Truth Produces Clear Stories\n    95→\n    96→Story 6-1 was derived directly from the UX spec mockup with the instruction \"reproduce EXACTLY.\" This eliminated ambiguity that previous dashboard stories suffered from, where developers \"interpreted\" the visual format. When a visual spec exists, stories should reference specific line numbers and include the target output verbatim.\n    97→\n    98→### L2: Code Review Catches Different Bugs Than Verification\n    99→\n   100→Across both stories, code review found 5 bugs (2 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM, 1 LOW). Verification found 0 additional functional bugs. This confirms the pattern from Epic 0.5: review catches logic and integration bugs; verification catches deployment and packaging bugs. Both phases serve different purposes and neither should be skipped.\n   101→\n   102→### L3: Extracting Closures Improves Testability\n   103→\n   104→Both stories benefited from extracting closure-scoped functions into importable modules. Story 6-1 split components into three files. Story 6-2 extracted `createLineProcessor` from a closure in `run.ts`. The pattern: if a function is defined inside another function's scope, it cannot be unit-tested. Extract it.\n   105→\n   106→### L4: Epic Numbering Collisions Cause Real Confusion\n   107→\n   108→The previous sprint had its own \"Epic 6\" (Brownfield Onboarding) which left a stale `epic-6-retrospective.md`. The create-story agent noted this as a misleading artifact. Session retros flagged it twice. Nobody cleaned it up between sessions. Epic numbering should be prefixed by sprint identifier (e.g., `opex-6` vs `overhaul-6`) or use globally unique numbers.\n   109→\n   110→### L5: Two-Story Epics Ship Fast but Skip Process Steps\n   111→\n   112→Epic 6 completed in a single day with two stories. However: no epic definition file, no sprint planning step, story files not synced to sprint status, proof documents not created. The speed is good; the process gaps compound over time when they become normalized behavior.\n   113→\n   114→---\n   115→\n   116→## Epic 0.5 Retro Action Item Status\n   117→\n   118→| # | Action | Status | Notes |\n   119→|---|--------|--------|-------|\n   120→| A1 | Fix `codeharness verify` presentation bug — FAIL on 6/6 pass | Not done | Not addressed in Epic 6. |\n   121→| A2 | Tag stories with `verification-tier` at planning time | Not done | Epic 6 stories weren't tagged. |\n   122→| A3 | Add E2E test for stream-JSON → parser → renderer pipeline | Done | Story 6-2 directly addresses this. |\n   123→| A4 | Enforce sprint change proposal for scope additions | Not done | Not addressed. |\n   124→| A5 | Fix story-status synchronization | Not done | Both 6-1 and 6-2 have status mismatches. |\n   125→| A6 | Remove `verification_run` pre-commit gate or make it context-aware | Not done | Not addressed. |\n   126→| A7 | Add integration test for package entry point exports | Not done | Not addressed. |\n   127→| A8 | Split package entry point into library + CLI bootstrap | Not done | Not addressed. |\n   128→\n   129→**Summary:** 1 of 8 action items from Epic 0.5 was resolved. 7 remain unaddressed. The pattern of carrying forward unresolved action items continues.\n   130→\n   131→---\n   132→\n   133→## Action Items\n   134→\n   135→| # | Action | Priority | Notes |\n   136→|---|--------|----------|-------|\n   137→| A1 | Fix cost accumulation data loss — buffer cost from events before `sprintInfo` init | High | Known bug shipped as tech debt. Cost display undercounts. |\n   138→| A2 | Bring `run.ts` under 300 lines (NFR9 compliance) — extract iteration count and stderr parsing | Medium | Currently 308 lines. Pre-existing violation. |\n   139→| A3 | Clean up epic numbering collision — establish sprint-prefixed or globally unique epic numbers | Medium | Two different \"Epic 6\" definitions exist. Caused confusion across 4+ session retros. |\n   140→| A4 | Fix story-status sync — either automate or enforce `codeharness sync` after story completion | Medium | Carried from Epic 0.5 A5, Epic 5 A5, Epic 4 A4. Six epics of divergence. |\n   141→| A5 | Add multi-byte UTF-8 chunk boundary test for `createLineProcessor` | Low | `StringDecoder` handles it but no test proves it. Flagged in 6-2 review. |\n   142→| A6 | Complete AC5 manual verification of 6-2 when next live story execution occurs | Low | Non-automatable. Needs real `codeharness run` with a backlog story. |\n   143→| A7 | Automate stale container cleanup before verification | Low | Infrastructure friction in every verify phase. `docker rm -f` before each run. |\n   144→\n   145→---\n   146→\n   147→## Metrics\n   148→\n   149→- **Stories planned:** 2\n   150→- **Stories completed:** 2\n   151→- **Stories failed:** 0\n   152→- **Code review cycles:** 1 per story (2 total; both passed on first review cycle with fixes)\n   153→- **Bugs caught in review:** 5 (2 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM, 1 LOW across both stories)\n   154→- **Bugs caught in verify:** 0\n   155→- **Total new tests:** ~184 (17 new/updated in 6-1 + integration test suite in 6-2)\n   156→- **Test suite at completion:** 2912 tests (2910 passing, 2 pre-existing failures in state.test.ts)\n   157→- **Files created:** 3 (ink-activity-components.tsx, ink-app.tsx, run-pipeline.test.ts)\n   158→- **Files modified:** 7 (ink-components.tsx, ink-renderer.tsx, run-helpers.ts, run.ts, ink-renderer.test.tsx, run-helpers.test.ts, sample-stream.ndjson fixture)\n   159→- **NFR9 violations:** 1 (run.ts at 308 lines — pre-existing, not introduced by this epic)\n   160→- **Implementation window:** 1 day (2026-03-21)\n   161→- **Epic 0.5 retro actions resolved:** 1 of 8\n   162→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01ByFBLT9ziGxFmVXofYDDPj","session_id":"d92c7bcb-37ff-4aa2-841f-ece7fabef071","uuid":"b2d56393-f2aa-44a0-b3c5-64b92a3f31f5","timestamp":"2026-03-21T12:44:43.610Z"}
